<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="187" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111/1798½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-11">11 <hi rend="smallcaps">March</hi>, 1915</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I think you are quite
                            right about this matter. We must be infinitely patient.</p>
                        <p>We can very properly, as these reports and complaints are brought to us,
                            ask that we be supplied with definite particulars and tangible proof,
                            and explain that without them it was impossible for us even to set the
                            processes of investigation afoot. But that, I think, is the most we can
                            do. I do not think that such letters as Mr. Lansing suggests, true and
                            justified in reason though they be, would be wise.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>